Outcome 2:
2.1. 122,865.9 ha of forest lands with rare biotopes have been identified in 33 forestries during 2018-2020.  
Passports for the protection of 21,814 ha of rare biotopes were identified and agreed on with respective forestries. 
A set of mandatory documents for their transfer under protection have been prepared by the Project and submitted to relevant state bodies for registration of such decisions;
2.2. Cumulatively 11 forestries envisage forestry management plans in line with sustainable use of protected biotopes. 
Forest management plans have been updated and approved for two (2) forestries: Dyatlovskoe and Ivievskoe. Also, project’s recommendations on necessary changes (to accommodate for sustainable use of biotopes) in management plans were prepared for nine (9) forestries. Revised plans for 9 forestries were prepared and submitted for approval to respective state bodies. 
Specific updates to forest management plans are: 
-	Changes on sustainable management of forest habitats were included in forest management plans of the Dyatlovskoe and Ivievskoe forestries. 
-	Recommended changes on sustainable management of forest habitats were prepared for forest management plans of the Stolinskoe, Vileyskoe, Kletskoe, Puhovichskoe, Smolevichskoe, Starobinskoe, Uzdenskoe, Minskoe, Zhlobinskoe forestries;
2.3. 87 employees total of forestries of the Ministry of Forestry have been trained since project start in the sustainable use of protected biotopes. 
A seminar was held in the Stolinski forestry with participation of staff of 13 forestries and State Forestry Planning Enterprize  Belgosles (47 participants total). Participating forest inventory specialists obtained theoretical knowledge and were trained in identification of rare and typical biotopes during forest inventory and organization of their subsequent sustainable use.
2.4. Proposals on ways of further use of forest hydro ameliorative systems on the area of 257,000 ha have been developed and agreed with the respective forestries (more than 30 forestries in 5 regions of the country).

Outcome 3:
3.1. Dikoe - no changes from the baseline - 250 ha  
Servech - 500 ha  were cleaned in 2018 from bushes and reeds. 
Belovezhskay Puscha National Park (landowner of Dikoe) decided to first optimize the hydro-regime on the pilot territory of Dikoe before starting works on removing excess biomass. Respective activities are planned by the National Park administration for 2022-2023. This was discussed on the PB meeting in December 2019 and approved. 
 In 2020, further works on optimization of the hydrological regime are undertaken at the Sevech fen, which will prevent overgrowth of the swamp with alder and birch on the whole lowland bog of 600 ha.  
3.2. 2020 monitoring results for:	 	  -      
Dikoe: 
Aquatic warbler - 20 males; 
Greater spotted eagle - 4-5 pairs;  
Long-term population trend of Aquatic warbler at Dikoe is decreasing due to the overgrowth of open marshes with bushes, in the short term, precipitations cause its population size to fluctuate to a greater degree.  
Servech:  
Aquatic warbler - 22-57 males; 
Curlew - 2 pairs; 
Great snipe - 10 males;
3.3. 950 ha of sedge fen mires (79% of EoP) have been restored by the project.  
The project has reached an agreement with the peat extracting factory operating in the Grodno Region that remaining 250 ha will be reweted at the factorys expense after the production (in line with the national regulatory framework) is completed in 2021-2022. 
3.4. In 2019-2020, pilot activities on creation of sedge communities were launched on 950 hectares of cultivated peat bog. 
3.5. As reported in the 2019, carbon dioxide emissions have been estimated prior to rewetting of forest and open peatlands and been registered at the level 10-20 tons per ha per year (the baseline level) 
Achieved GHG emissions reduction at these sites will be assessed in 2021 once rewetting activities at 12,000 ha have been fully completed.
3.6. 0 (no change from the baseline)  
Having studied the genetics of the Nalibokski bison micro population, a recommendation has been made by the National Academy of Sciences of Belarus to transfer genetically valuable bison to enrich the genetic diversity of the local micro population. The completed study and the recommendation of the Academy of Science has created a scientific framework/justification for the project to proceed with the transfer as was envisaged in the prodoc.  
As such, in 2020-2021 it is planned to exchange two (2) females from Nalibokskaya Pushcha for two (2) males from Moldova. The transfer of bison from Moldova (not originally in the prodoc) is explained by the genetic differentiation between the Moldovan and Belarusian-Polish populations of bison. Both sides are interested in this exchange to increase the stability of national bison populations.
3.7. Six (6) genetic passports prepared for the Nalibokski micro population of the European bison.
3.8. Population size increased from 2 males in 2017 to 30 males in 2020 (through translocation). 
The International Study Group “Aquatic warbler Conservation Team” (includes more than 30 representatives from EU and Eastern Europe countries) recognized that a breakthrough in Aquatic warbler conservation had been achieved through the translocation methodology developed by the project.
3.9. 22 breeding pairs of greater spotted eagle were observed in Olmay Mires.
3.10. No change from the baseline.  
A joint research collaboration on breeding success is planned for 2021-2022 with another international TA project titled Polesie , where this issue is one of the priorities.
3.11. Cumulatively, 38 artificial nests have been established on plots in 2019 and 2020 for such rare bird species as big eagle, owl, bearded eagle: 
-	Six (6) in the Olmany bogs; 
-	Twenty-one (21) in the Zvanets reserve; 
-	Eleven (11) in the Sporovski reserve.
3.12. National status of 13 invertebrate species and 5 mollusk species was assessed in Brest, Minsk, Grodno and Vitebsk regions, similar works in Gomel and Mogilev regions are underway.  
The data on distribution, population status, ecology and threats to the above-mentioned species were obtained. Dolomedes plantaires, Unio crassus have been inhabited in the habitats where these species have disappeared and newly created populations are being monitored.   
New Cerambyx cerdo habitats (2 new populations) have been restored and preparatory works have been carried out to relocate to new Unio crassus habitats (2 new populations). 
Development of corresponding Action plans on conservation of 13 invertebrate species and 5 mollusk species is planned to be completed in late 2020-2021

